===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|educatio|ēducātiō|a breeding, bringing up, rearing}} < {{term|lang=la|educare|ēducāre|to educate}} < {{term|educere|ēducēre}}; see [[educate#Etymology|educate]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ɛdjuːkeɪʃn/}}
* {{audio|en-us-education.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|eɪʃǝn}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{uncountable}} The process or art of [[imparting]] [[knowledge]], [[skill]] and [[judgment]]
#: ''A good teacher is essential for a good '''education'''''
# {{countable}} [[fact|Facts]], [[skill]]s and [[idea]]s that have been [[learnt]], either [[formally]] or [[informally]]
#: ''He has had a classical '''education'''.''
#: ''The '''educations''' our children receive depend on their economic status.''

